    key: "Cash is the physical money available to a business at any given time, while profit is the accounting surplus of revenues over costs — a business can be profitable but still run out of cash.",
    body: "This is one of the most important distinctions in business finance. A business that sells goods on credit may show high profit in its income statement but have very little actual cash in the bank because customers have not yet paid. Conversely, a business may receive cash (e.g., upfront subscriptions) before recording it as profit. Key differences:",
