cost: [
  {
    title: "Types of Cost — Fixed, Variable, Marginal, Direct, and Indirect",
    key: "Businesses classify costs to aid in pricing, budgeting, profit calculation, and decision-making.",
    body: "Understanding cost types is fundamental to both the JUPEB exam and real business management. Each type of cost behaves differently as output changes:",
    table: {
      headers: ["Cost Type", "Definition", "Behaviour with Output", "Nigerian Example"],
      rows: [
        ["Fixed Cost", "Costs that do not change regardless of how much is produced", "Remains the same whether output is 0 or 1,000 units", "Factory rent in Aba (paid monthly regardless of production), management salaries, insurance premiums"],
        ["Variable Cost", "Costs that change directly in proportion to output", "Increases as output increases; zero if nothing is produced", "Raw cassava bought by a garri processor — more cassava needed as more garri is made; fuel, packaging materials"],
        ["Semi-variable (Mixed) Cost", "Has both fixed and variable elements", "Fixed base + variable element per unit", "Electricity bill — fixed standing charge + variable units consumed in production"],
        ["Marginal Cost", "The additional cost of producing one more unit of output", "Relevant for decisions about whether to increase output", "If producing 500 bags of rice costs ₦500,000 and 501 bags costs ₦500,900 — the marginal cost of the 501st bag is ₦900"],
        ["Direct Cost", "Costs that can be traced directly to a specific product or job", "Varies with the product", "Flour and butter used to make bread at a bakery in Kano; fabric used by a tailor per outfit"],
        ["Indirect Cost (Overhead)", "Costs that cannot be directly attributed to one product — shared across all products", "Fixed or semi-variable; allocated/apportioned to products", "Factory lighting, supervisor salary, general advertising, factory rent shared across all products"]
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    title: "Uses of Cost Information",
    key: "Cost information is used for pricing decisions, profit calculation, budgeting, performance measurement, and strategic decision-making.",
    body: "Cost data is the foundation of sound business management. Key uses include: Pricing — knowing costs ensures selling price exceeds cost (cost-plus pricing: price = cost + desired mark-up). In Nigeria, where raw material costs fluctuate with exchange rates, accurate cost data helps businesses adjust prices appropriately. Profit calculation — Profit = Revenue − Total Costs. Understanding which costs are fixed and which are variable helps in calculating profit at different levels of output. Budgeting — cost information allows managers to set realistic spending targets and identify areas of waste. Make-or-buy decisions — should the business produce a component itself or buy it from a supplier? Comparing internal production cost with supplier price guides this decision. Shutdown decisions — if variable costs exceed revenue (contribution is negative), a business should consider shutting down a product line. Investment appraisal — cost projections are essential inputs for evaluating whether a new investment will be profitable."
  },
  {
    title: "Break-Even Analysis — Concepts and Formula",
    key: "Break-even analysis identifies the output level at which total revenue equals total cost — the point of neither profit nor loss.",
    body: "Key break-even concepts and formulae:",
    table: {
      headers: ["Concept", "Formula", "Explanation", "Example (Nigerian Bakery)"],
      rows: [
        ["Contribution per Unit", "Selling Price per Unit − Variable Cost per Unit", "The amount each unit sold contributes toward covering fixed costs and then generating profit", "Bread sells for ₦500; variable cost = ₦300. Contribution = ₦200 per loaf"],
        ["Break-Even Point (Units)", "Fixed Costs ÷ Contribution per Unit", "Number of units that must be sold to cover all costs", "Fixed costs = ₦400,000. BEP = ₦400,000 ÷ ₦200 = 2,000 loaves per month"],
        ["Break-Even Revenue", "Break-Even Units × Selling Price", "Revenue needed to break even", "2,000 × ₦500 = ₦1,000,000 per month"],
        ["Margin of Safety (Units)", "Actual Output − Break-Even Output", "How much output can fall before a loss is made", "If bakery sells 2,500 loaves: Margin of Safety = 2,500 − 2,000 = 500 loaves"],
        ["Margin of Safety (%)", "(Margin of Safety ÷ Actual Output) × 100", "Safety cushion as a percentage of actual sales", "(500 ÷ 2,500) × 100 = 20% — output can fall 20% before a loss"],
        ["Profit at Given Output", "(Output − BEP Units) × Contribution per Unit", "Profit once break-even is exceeded", "(2,500 − 2,000) × ₦200 = ₦100,000 profit"]
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    title: "Uses and Limitations of Break-Even Analysis",
    key: "Break-even analysis is a useful planning and decision-making tool but relies on simplifying assumptions that may not hold in the real world.",
    body: "",
    table: {
      headers: ["Uses of Break-Even Analysis", "Limitations of Break-Even Analysis"],
      rows: [
        ["Helps determine minimum sales target needed to avoid loss", "Assumes all output is sold — in reality, businesses may have unsold stock"],
        ["Assists in pricing decisions — shows impact of price changes on break-even point", "Assumes selling price is constant — in Nigeria, businesses frequently offer discounts and negotiate prices"],
        ["Evaluates the impact of cost changes — e.g., if diesel price rises, how does BEP change?", "Assumes costs behave in a perfectly linear fashion — in reality, bulk discounts make variable costs non-linear"],
        ["Useful for launching a new product — shows how many units must be sold to justify launch", "Ignores the time value of money — ₦1 million today is worth more than ₦1 million next year"],
        ["Helps assess risk — the margin of safety shows how much cushion the business has", "Only applies to a single product — multi-product businesses need more complex analysis"],
        ["Useful for 'what-if' scenario analysis (sensitivity analysis)", "Uses historical cost data which may not reflect current conditions — especially problematic in Nigeria's inflationary environment where costs change rapidly"]
      ]
    }
  },
],

